A child's initial social and relational environment might affect their educational success. Family wealth, education, and structure may affect a child's schooling, according to research. Low-income kids are more likely to attend under-resourced schools, lack instructional resources and technology, and have fewer extracurricular options. Low-income kids may struggle academically and graduate. Parental education affects a child's education. Educational resources and assistance are more probable for children of educated parents, which may improve educational performance. Family structure also affects schooling. Single-parent families are associated with poorer academic attainment and graduation rates. Social capital—networks people's and resources—can also affect educational success. Social capital—access to educational resources and networks—improves academic performance. In conclusion, a child's initial social and relational environment may affect their educational success. Family income, parental education, family structure, and social capital might affect a child's schooling. 